@hadess I figured it may not be, but it used to work for me without an issue, so I wanted to make note of the regression (I still boot into gdm on my system).

The functionality offered in gnome-control-center is helpful for me without finding several other smaller utilities to manage this functionality. I imagine there are other people who feel this way about its usefulness, but I also acknowledge it is probably a minority of users.

So, it is your call on what to do here. If I can help debug the issue further, I'm happy to help, but if the decision is to close it now as wontfix, I understand.

@hadess I see. As a happy user of the gnome-control-center outside of a GNOME desktop for a few years, this makes me a little sad. I'm not sure if I understand why this decision was made. I understand the interest in maintaining the best-possible GNOME experience, but if other people benefit from using GNOME utilities and tools outside of the GNOME desktop, I don't understand why it should be explicitly difficult for others to use GNOME utilities.

As a user, I acknowledge that GNOME utilities like gnome-control-center may not always work as expected in a non-GNOME environment, but I am aware of that too when using them. If something breaks because I don't have something installed, I will not blame GNOME developers for it. But when something is working well already, and then it is explicitly made to not be interoperable, it does disappoint me.

I don't mean to debate this, but I am curious to better understand this decision or why the developer team felt it was important to make this change.

