@fujimotos I have to admit I’m massively out of date on what Windows users actually use to extract their archives these days.  Windows didn’t have any ZIP support at all when I started using it, and then I kind of transitioned from WinZIP to WinRAR to 7-Zip without ever using the built-in tools.  But all that became irrelevant to me when Windows XP was still current, and I’ve no idea what’s relevant to Windows users now.

Of course it’s OK to create archives that can’t be read on Windows (that’s what most of the file-roller options do, after all).  I agree with you in that it’s not OK to do so intermittently depending on which other packages happen to be installed on the system.  But I also think that it isn’t fair to have an option that exists specifically to provide security, but doesn’t.

The issue is communicating the compatibility issues to the user.  As far as I can see, the “New Archive” dialog (unlike the “Create Archive” dialog invoked from the context menu in Nautilus) does not attempt to explain anything at all about format compatibility and just offers a humongous list of formats instead.  It’s not clear to me how the (even subtler) issue of AES in ZIP could fit in there.

